# SECTION 5: KTU 2024 Scheme Examination Question Bank & Topic Recap

## 5.1 Part A Questions (3 Marks Each)

### Question 1: [KTU University Exam – Dec 2023]
**Explain how a two-dimensional array is stored in memory in C. What is row-major order?**

**Model Answer (3 marks):**

In C, a two-dimensional array is stored in **contiguous memory locations** using **row-major order**. This means that the elements of the first row are stored first, followed by the elements of the second row, and so on.

For a 2D array `A[m][n]`, the element `A[i][j]` is stored at the memory address:
$$\text{Address} = \text{Base} + (i \times n + j) \times \text{sizeof(data\_type)}$$

For example, the array `int a[3][3]` storing `{{1,2,3},{4,5,6},{7,8,9}}` is stored in memory as: `1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8, 9` — all in sequential bytes. This layout affects cache performance and pointer arithmetic in C. **(3 marks)**

---

### Question 2: [KTU University Exam – June 2024]
**State the precondition required to perform matrix multiplication. Why is it necessary?**

**Model Answer (3 marks):**

For matrix multiplication `C = A × B` to be valid, the **number of columns of matrix A** must equal the **number of rows of matrix B**. If `A` is of size `m × n` and `B` is of size `n × p`, then the resulting product `C` will be of size `m × p`.

**Why it is necessary:** The element `C[i][j]` is computed as the dot product of the `i`-th row of A (which has `n` elements) and the `j`-th column of B (which also has `n` elements). If the dimensions don't match (`n_A ≠ n_B`), the dot product cannot be defined because the row vector and column vector would have different lengths, making the operation mathematically undefined. **(3 marks)**

---

## 5.2 Part B Questions (14 Marks Each)

### Question A (14 Marks) — Matrix Multiplication

**[KTU University Exam – Model Paper 2024, Modified]**

**(a)** Write a complete C program to read two matrices `A` (of size `m × n`) and `B` (of size `n × p`) from the user, compute their product `C = A × B`, and display the result. Validate that the dimensions are compatible for multiplication. **(7 marks)**

**(b)** Explain the logic of matrix multiplication with the help of the mathematical expression for `C[i][j]`. Using a `2 × 3` and `3 × 2` example, demonstrate the computation step by step. **(7 marks)**

#### Model Solution

**(a) Complete C Program (7 marks):**

```c
#include <stdio.h>

int main() {
    int m, n, p, i, j, k;
    int A[10][10], B[10][10], C[10][10];

    printf("Enter rows and columns of matrix A (m n): ");
    scanf("%d %d", &m, &n);
    printf("Enter rows and columns of matrix B (n p): ");
    scanf("%d %d", &n, &p);

    if (n <= 0) {
        printf("Error: Dimensions incompatible for multiplication.\n");
        return 1;
    }

    printf("Enter elements of matrix A (%d x %d):\n", m, n);
    for (i = 0; i < m; i++)
        for (j = 0; j < n; j++)
            scanf("%d", &A[i][j]);

    printf("Enter elements of matrix B (%d x %d):\n", n, p);
    for (i = 0; i < n; i++)
        for (j = 0; j < p; j++)
            scanf("%d", &B[i][j]);

    // Initialize C to zero
    for (i = 0; i < m; i++)
        for (j = 0; j < p; j++)
            C[i][j] = 0;

    // Multiplication
    for (i = 0; i < m; i++) {
        for (j = 0; j < p; j++) {
            for (k = 0; k < n; k++) {
                C[i][j] += A[i][k] * B[k][j];
            }
        }
    }

    printf("Resultant Matrix C = A x B:\n");
    for (i = 0; i < m; i++) {
        for (j = 0; j < p; j++) {
            printf("%d\t", C[i][j]);
        }
        printf("\n");
    }

    return 0;
}
```

**Key Evaluation Points (Examiner's Checklist):**
- Header inclusion: `#include <stdio.h>` ✓
- Correct declaration of 2D arrays ✓
- Input prompts for dimensions ✓
- Three nested loops for multiplication ✓
- Initialization of result matrix to 0 ✓ **(7 marks)**

**(b) Mathematical Explanation and Example (7 marks):**

**Logic:** Each element `C[i][j]` is the **dot product** of the `i`-th row of `A` and the `j`-th column of `B`:

$$
C[i][j] = \sum_{k=0}^{n-1} A[i][k] \times B[k][j]
$$

**Worked Example:**

Let
$$
A = \begin{bmatrix} 1 & 2 & 3 \\ 4 & 5 & 6 \end{bmatrix} \quad (2 \times 3), \quad
B = \begin{bmatrix} 7 & 8 \\ 9 & 10 \\ 11 & 12 \end{bmatrix} \quad (3 \times 2)
$$

Result `C` is of size `2 × 2`.

**Step 1: Compute C[0][0]**
$$C[0][0] = (1 \times 7) + (2 \times 9) + (3 \times 11) = 7 + 18 + 33 = 58$$

**Step 2: Compute C[0][1]**
$$C[0][1] = (1 \times 8) + (2 \times 10) + (3 \times 12) = 8 + 20 + 36 = 64$$

**Step 3: Compute C[1][0]**
$$C[1][0] = (4 \times 7) + (5 \times 9) + (6 \times 11) = 28 + 45 + 66 = 139$$

**Step 4: Compute C[1][1]**
$$C[1][1] = (4 \times 8) + (5 \times 10) + (6 \times 12) = 32 + 50 + 72 = 154$$

$$
\therefore C = \begin{bmatrix} 58 & 64 \\ 139 & 154 \end{bmatrix}
$$

**7 marks breakdown:** 2 marks for formula, 4 marks for stepwise computation, 1 mark for final matrix. **(7 marks)**

---

### Question B (14 Marks) — Matrix Transpose and Symmetry

**[KTU University Exam – Model Paper 2024, Modified]**

**(a)** Write a complete C program to read an `n × n` square matrix from the user and check whether it is a **symmetric matrix**. Display an appropriate message. **(7 marks)**

**(b)** Write a complete C program to find the **transpose** of a given `m × n` matrix and display both the original and the transposed matrix. Explain the index transformation logic used. **(7 marks)**

#### Model Solution

**(a) Symmetric Matrix Check (7 marks):**

```c
#include <stdio.h>

int main() {
    int n, i, j, flag = 1;
    int A[10][10];

    printf("Enter the size of square matrix (n): ");
    scanf("%d", &n);

    printf("Enter matrix elements:\n");
    for (i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        for (j = 0; j < n; j++) {
            scanf("%d", &A[i][j]);
        }
    }

    // Check symmetry
    for (i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        for (j = 0; j < n; j++) {
            if (A[i][j] != A[j][i]) {
                flag = 0;
                break;
            }
        }
        if (flag == 0) break;
    }

    if (flag == 1)
        printf("The matrix is SYMMETRIC (A = A^T).\n");
    else
        printf("The matrix is NOT SYMMETRIC.\n");

    return 0;
}
```

**Logic:** A matrix is symmetric if `A[i][j] == A[j][i]` for all valid `i, j`. The `flag` variable tracks whether any mismatch is found. Using `break` statements ensures the loop exits early as soon as a mismatch is detected, improving efficiency. **(7 marks)**

**(b) Transpose Program (7 marks):**

```c
#include <stdio.h>

int main() {
    int m, n, i, j;
    int A[10][10], T[10][10];

    printf("Enter rows and columns: ");
    scanf("%d %d", &m, &n);

    printf("Enter matrix A elements:\n");
    for (i = 0; i < m; i++)
        for (j = 0; j < n; j++)
            scanf("%d", &A[i][j]);

    // Compute transpose
    for (i = 0; i < m; i++) {
        for (j = 0; j < n; j++) {
            T[j][i] = A[i][j];
        }
    }

    // Display original
    printf("\nOriginal Matrix A:\n");
    for (i = 0; i < m; i++) {
        for (j = 0; j < n; j++) {
            printf("%d\t", A[i][j]);
        }
        printf("\n");
    }

    // Display transpose
    printf("\nTranspose A^T:\n");
    for (i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        for (j = 0; j < m; j++) {
            printf("%d\t", T[i][j]);
        }
        printf("\n");
    }

    return 0;
}
```

**Index Transformation Logic:**

The key transformation in transpose is the **swapping of indices**:
- **Original:** `A[i][j]` accesses the `i`-th row, `j`-th column.
- **Transpose:** `T[j][i] = A[i][j]` places the element at row `j`, column `i` of `T`.
- **Result:** If `A` is `m × n`, then `T` becomes `n × m` (rows and columns swap).

> [!WARNING]
> **KTU Examiner's Valuation Warning — Common Pitfalls:**
> 1. **Forgetting to initialize the result matrix `C` to 0 in multiplication** — garbage values will accumulate. (**−1 to −2 marks**)
> 2. **Off-by-one errors in loops** — using `<=` instead of `<` causes array out-of-bounds access. (**−1 mark**)
> 3. **Confusing row and column dimensions** in transpose output loops. Remember, the dimensions **swap** in transpose. (**−1 mark**)
> 4. **Not reading the user input correctly** — forgetting `&` in `scanf("%d", &A[i][j])` is a classic error. (**−1 mark**)
> 5. **Missing header `#include <stdio.h>`** — program won't compile. (**−0.5 mark**)
> 6. **Assuming square matrix for transpose** — transpose works for any `m × n` matrix, not just square ones. (**−1 mark**)
> 7. **Forgetting the `break` statement in symmetry check** — wastes computation but doesn't lose correctness; still, examiners may deduct for poor practice.

