## 5.3 Topic Recap & Important Things to Remember

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Rapid Revision Checklist — Matrix Processing in C:**

- ✅ A matrix is stored as a **2D array** in C, declared as `type name[ROWS][COLS]`.
- ✅ C uses **row-major order**: elements of each row are stored contiguously in memory.
- ✅ **Array indexing starts at 0** — last valid index is `size - 1`.
- ✅ For **addition/subtraction**: both matrices must have the **same dimensions**.
- ✅ For **multiplication** `A × B`: `columns of A = rows of B`; result size is `rows of A × columns of B`.
- ✅ Multiplication requires **three nested loops** and the result matrix must be **initialized to 0**.
- ✅ **Transpose swaps rows and columns**: `T[j][i] = A[i][j]`. Output dimensions are `n × m` if input is `m × n`.
- ✅ **Trace** is the sum of diagonal elements `A[i][i]` — only defined for square matrices.
- ✅ A matrix is **symmetric** if `A[i][j] == A[j][i]` for all `i, j`.
- ✅ Always use `&` operator in `scanf` for non-array variables.
- ✅ Initialize arrays properly before use (especially result matrices in multiplication) to avoid garbage values.
- ✅ Use clear, descriptive variable names and proper indentation for readability and marks.
- ✅ Common time complexities: Addition/Subtraction = **O(m × n)**; Multiplication = **O(m × n × p)**; Transpose = **O(m × n)**.

> [!NOTE]
> **High-Yield Exam Tip:** In KTU exams, you will almost always be asked to **write a complete, compilable C program** with proper `#include`, `main()` function, variable declarations, input, logic, and formatted output. Practice writing programs on paper within time limits to build fluency. Also, remember that the `printf` format specifier `\t` (tab) is commonly used to align matrix output in columns — this is expected and earns you style marks.
