# SECTION 1: Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

## 1.1 Command Line Arguments — Formal KTU Definition

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Command Line Arguments** are the string values that are passed to a C program at the time of execution directly from the operating system command interpreter (shell/terminal). They are received by the `main()` function through two built-in parameters: `argc` (argument count) and `argv` (argument vector).

The standard KTU 2024 Scheme signature is:

```c
int main(int argc, char *argv[])
```

Where:
- **`argc`** (Argument Count) — an integer storing the number of command-line arguments passed, **including the program name itself**. Minimum value is **1**.
- **`argv`** (Argument Vector) — an array of character pointers (strings), where `argv[0]` holds the program name and `argv[1]` through `argv[argc-1]` hold the actual user-supplied arguments.

### Conceptual Analogy — The "Courier Delivery" Model

> [!NOTE]
> **Real-world analogy:** Imagine you walk into a courier office and hand over three sealed envelopes along with a slip that says "I have sent 3 envelopes plus this slip." The clerk uses the slip to know *how many* envelopes to expect, and opens each envelope to read the *content*.
>
> - The **slip** = `argc` (tells how many items to expect).
> - The **envelopes** = `argv[]` (the actual string data, each addressable by its index).
> - The **first envelope** is always the program's own name (the courier company's ID slip).

This is why `argv[0]` is always non-empty — it is automatically supplied by the OS, and the user-supplied arguments begin from `argv[1]`.

---

## 1.2 Structures — Formal KTU Definition

> [!IMPORTANT]
> A **Structure** in C is a user-defined composite data type that groups together logically related variables (called **members** or **fields**) of *possibly different data types* under a single name. It is declared using the keyword `struct` and is stored in a **contiguous block of memory** (subject to internal padding by the compiler).

The general KTU-prescribed syntax is:

```c
struct TagName {
    data_type member1;
    data_type member2;
    ...
    data_type memberN;
};
```

### Conceptual Analogy — The "Student ID Card" Model

> [!NOTE]
> **Real-world analogy:** A university ID card bundles *different kinds* of information about one student: Name (text), Roll Number (integer), CGPA (float), and Hosteller status (character). A structure does the same for one logical entity in memory.
>
> - The **ID card template** = the `struct` definition.
> - An **actual physical card** belonging to a specific student = a *structure variable*.
> - The **fields printed on the card** = structure *members*.
> - A **rack of 60 ID cards** in the HOD's office = an *Array of Structures*.

Unlike arrays (where all elements must be of the *same* type), a structure allows **heterogeneous data** under one umbrella — making it the foundation of records, linked lists, trees, and database rows in C.

---

## 1.3 Why These Concepts Matter in KTU Examinations

> [!TIP]
> - **Command Line Arguments** frequently appear in KTU university questions on writing programs that accept inputs (e.g., a program that takes two numbers as command-line input and prints their sum).
> - **Structures** are the single most heavily tested topic in Module 3 and recur in Module 4 (pointers to structures, self-referential structures, linked lists).
> - Mastering **Array of Structures** and **Passing Structures to Functions** is the gateway to writing modular, real-world C programs (payroll systems, student databases, inventory management).

