# SECTION 2: Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Formula Sheet

## 2.1 Command Line Arguments — Operational Mechanics

### Step-by-Step Execution Flow

1. **Compilation:** The C compiler compiles `program.c` into an executable `program.exe` (Windows) or `./a.out` (Linux).
2. **Invocation:** The user types the executable name followed by space-separated arguments in the terminal:

   ```bash
   ./a.out 25  Hello  3.14
   ```

3. **OS Allocation:** The operating system's command shell parses this input, places each token in memory, and then invokes `main()` passing two values:
   - `argc = 4` (program name + 3 arguments).
   - `argv = {"a.out", "25", "Hello", "3.14"}` (an array of 4 pointers to char).
4. **String Nature:** All arguments arrive as **strings** (character arrays). Even `"25"` is the character sequence `'2'`, `'5'`, `'\0'` — *not* the integer 25.
5. **Conversion Required:** To perform arithmetic, you must convert strings using library functions:
   - `atoi(argv[i])` → converts to `int`.
   - `atof(argv[i])` → converts to `double`.
   - `atol(argv[i])` → converts to `long int`.

> [!WARNING]
> **KTU Pitfall:** A common mistake is writing `int x = argv[1];` which causes a **compilation error** because `argv[1]` is a `char *`, not an `int`. The correct form is `int x = atoi(argv[1]);`.

### Memory Layout of `argv`

`argv` is itself an array of pointers. Each pointer points to a null-terminated string. The size of `argv` is `argc`.

---

## 2.2 Structures — Deep Theory

### 2.2.1 Defining a Structure Variable (Three KTU-Approved Styles)

| Style | Syntax | KTU Preference |
|---|---|---|
| **Style 1: Tag + Separate Declaration** | `struct Student { ... };` then `struct Student s1;` | ✅ Most preferred — clean separation |
| **Style 2: Tag + Inline Declaration** | `struct Student { ... } s1, s2;` | ✅ Acceptable — common in KTU answers |
| **Style 3: Typedef Style** | `typedef struct { ... } Student;` then `Student s1;` | ✅ Used when many variables needed |

### 2.2.2 Accessing Members — The Two KTU Operators

| Operator | Symbol | Used With | KTU Rule |
|---|---|---|---|
| **Dot Operator** | `.` | Direct structure variable (`struct Student s1;`) | `s1.rollNo` |
| **Arrow Operator** | `->` | Pointer to structure (`struct Student *ptr = &s1;`) | `ptr->rollNo` |

The relationship is mathematically expressed as:

$$ptr \rightarrow member \equiv (*ptr).member$$

This equivalence is a **high-yield KTU formula** — both expressions are identical and produce the same machine code.

### 2.2.3 Size of a Structure

The compiler inserts **padding bytes** to align members to word boundaries for performance:

$$sizeof(struct\ Tag) \geq \sum_{i=1}^{N} sizeof(member_i)$$

For KTU purposes, you may assume the inequality becomes an equality for `char` members, but for mixed types (with `int` and `double`), padding applies.

---

## 2.3 Array of Structures — Theory

An **Array of Structures** is a collection of structure variables stored contiguously, accessed by index. The KTU-recommended declaration is:

```c
struct Student {
    int rollNo;
    char name[50];
    float marks;
};

struct Student class[60];   // Array of 60 Student records
```

Access the *i*-th student's roll number as `class[i].rollNo`. This is the bedrock of all database-style programs.

---

## 2.4 Passing Structure to Function — The Two KTU Methods

| Method | Syntax | Pros | Cons |
|---|---|---|---|
| **Pass by Value** | `void display(struct Student s)` | Original data is safe; immutable copy | Memory overhead for large structures |
| **Pass by Address (Pointer)** | `void display(struct Student *s)` | Fast, no copy, can modify original | Original data can be altered accidentally |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU 2024 Scheme emphasis:** Both methods are tested. Pass-by-address is preferred for large structures (e.g., arrays of structures) for performance. When passing by address, use the arrow operator `s->rollNo` inside the function.

### Returning a Structure

Functions can also *return* structures. The return type is the structure tag:

```c
struct Point add(struct Point p1, struct Point p2);
```

---

## 2.5 KTU High-Yield Formula / Cheat Sheet

> [!TIP]
> Memorize the following table — it covers **80% of Part A and Part B** questions on this topic.

| # | Concept | KTU Rule / Formula | Notes |
|---|---|---|---|
| 1 | `argc` minimum value | $argc_{min} = 1$ | Always ≥ 1 (program name) |
| 2 | `argv[0]` content | Program name / executable path | OS-supplied, never user input |
| 3 | `argv[argc]` value | `NULL` pointer | Marks end of argument list |
| 4 | String-to-int conversion | `int x = atoi(argv[i]);` | Requires `<stdlib.h>` |
| 5 | String-to-float conversion | `float x = atof(argv[i]);` | Returns `double` |
| 6 | Member access (variable) | `s.member` | Dot operator |
| 7 | Member access (pointer) | `ptr->member` | Arrow operator |
| 8 | Dot-Arrow equivalence | $ptr \rightarrow m \equiv (*ptr).m$ | Always true |
| 9 | Struct size (approx.) | $sizeof(s) \geq \sum sizeof(m_i)$ | Padding may increase |
| 10 | Pass by value declaration | `void f(struct Tag s)` | Copy is made |
| 11 | Pass by address declaration | `void f(struct Tag *s)` | No copy; use `->` |
| 12 | `typedef` shortcut | `typedef struct Tag { ... } Alias;` | Use `Alias` as new type name |

> **Engineering utility:** Structures model real-world records — student databases, employee payrolls, GPS coordinate pairs (`struct Point { double lat, lon; }`), and 3D graphics vertices. Command line arguments power scripting, batch automation, and CI/CD pipelines (e.g., `gcc file.c -o file` passes `-o` and `file` as args to the compiler).

