## 3.1 Program 1: Sum of Two Numbers via Command Line Arguments

### Problem Statement
*(Model KTU Question)* — Write a C program to accept **two integers** as command-line arguments and print their sum. If fewer than 2 arguments are provided, display an error message.

### Complete Code

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>     // Required for atoi()

int main(int argc, char *argv[])
{
    int num1, num2, sum;

    // Step 1: Validate the argument count
    if (argc != 3) {
        printf("Usage: %s <num1> <num2>\n", argv[0]);
        return 1;       // Non-zero exit indicates error
    }

    // Step 2: Convert string arguments to integers
    num1 = atoi(argv[1]);
    num2 = atoi(argv[2]);

    // Step 3: Compute and display
    sum = num1 + num2;
    printf("Sum of %d and %d = %d\n", num1, num2, sum);

    return 0;   // Successful termination
}
```

### Compilation and Execution

```bash
gcc sum.c -o sum
./sum 45 78
```

### Sample Output

```
Sum of 45 and 78 = 123
```

### Line-by-Line Analytical Matrix

| Line(s) | Code | KTU Concept Mapped | Explanation |
|---|---|---|---|
| 1 | `#include <stdio.h>` | Header for I/O | Brings in `printf` |
| 2 | `#include <stdlib.h>` | Header for conversion | Brings in `atoi` |
| 4 | `int main(int argc, char *argv[])` | KTU-mandated signature | Receives OS-supplied args |
| 8 | `if (argc != 3)` | Validation of `argc` | Expected: program name + 2 args |
| 9 | `printf("Usage: %s ...", argv[0])` | Accessing program name | `argv[0]` is the executable |
| 10 | `return 1;` | Error exit code | Tells OS failure occurred |
| 14 | `num1 = atoi(argv[1]);` | String-to-int conversion | KTU 2024 high-yield point |
| 18 | `printf("Sum ... = %d\n", sum);` | Display result | Uses `%d` for int |

