## 3.2 Program 2: Student Structure — Define, Declare, Access

### Problem Statement
Define a structure `Student` with members `rollNo` (int), `name` (char array of 30), and `marks` (float). Declare one variable, read values from the user, and display them.

### Complete Code

```c
#include <stdio.h>

// Step 1: Define the structure template
struct Student {
    int rollNo;
    char name[30];
    float marks;
};

int main(void)
{
    // Step 2: Declare a structure variable
    struct Student s1;

    // Step 3: Read values from the user
    printf("Enter roll number: ");
    scanf("%d", &s1.rollNo);

    printf("Enter name: ");
    scanf("%s", s1.name);          // No '&' for char arrays

    printf("Enter marks: ");
    scanf("%f", &s1.marks);

    // Step 4: Display the values
    printf("\n--- Student Details ---\n");
    printf("Roll No : %d\n", s1.rollNo);
    printf("Name    : %s\n", s1.name);
    printf("Marks   : %.2f\n", s1.marks);

    return 0;
}
```

### Sample Run

```
Enter roll number: 23
Enter name: Anu
Enter marks: 89.5

--- Student Details ---
Roll No : 23
Name    : Anu
Marks   : 89.50
```

### Analytical Matrix

| Code Snippet | KTU Concept | Note |
|---|---|---|
| `struct Student { ... };` | Structure definition | Ends with semicolon — KTU 2024 trap |
| `struct Student s1;` | Declaring structure variable | Reserves `sizeof(Student)` bytes |
| `&s1.rollNo` | Address of int member | `&` required for `scanf` |
| `s1.name` | Char array (decays to pointer) | `scanf("%s", s1.name)` needs no `&` |
| `s1.marks` | Float member | Use `%f` format specifier |

