## 3.3 Program 3: Array of Structures — Student Database

### Problem Statement
*(Common 14-mark KTU question)* — Write a C program using an **array of structures** to store and display the records of `N` students (roll no, name, marks in 3 subjects, and total). Use functions to read and display.

### Complete Code

```c
#include <stdio.h>

#define MAX 50

struct Student {
    int rollNo;
    char name[30];
    float m1, m2, m3, total;
};

// Function prototypes
void readStudents(struct Student s[], int n);
void displayStudents(struct Student s[], int n);

int main(void)
{
    struct Student class[MAX];
    int n, i;

    printf("Enter number of students: ");
    scanf("%d", &n);

    if (n <= 0 || n > MAX) {
        printf("Invalid number. Must be 1..%d\n", MAX);
        return 1;
    }

    readStudents(class, n);

    // Compute total for each student
    for (i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        class[i].total = class[i].m1 + class[i].m2 + class[i].m3;
    }

    displayStudents(class, n);

    return 0;
}

// Function to read n students
void readStudents(struct Student s[], int n)
{
    int i;
    for (i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        printf("\nStudent %d\n", i + 1);
        printf("  Roll No: ");
        scanf("%d", &s[i].rollNo);
        printf("  Name   : ");
        scanf("%s", s[i].name);
        printf("  Mark 1 : ");
        scanf("%f", &s[i].m1);
        printf("  Mark 2 : ");
        scanf("%f", &s[i].m2);
        printf("  Mark 3 : ");
        scanf("%f", &s[i].m3);
    }
}

// Function to display n students
void displayStudents(struct Student s[], int n)
{
    int i;
    printf("\n%-10s %-15s %-8s %-8s %-8s %-8s\n",
           "Roll", "Name", "M1", "M2", "M3", "Total");
    printf("------------------------------------------------------------\n");
    for (i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        printf("%-10d %-15s %-8.2f %-8.2f %-8.2f %-8.2f\n",
               s[i].rollNo, s[i].name,
               s[i].m1, s[i].m2, s[i].m3, s[i].total);
    }
}
```

### Analytical Matrix

| Concept | Implementation | KTU Insight |
|---|---|---|
| Array of structures | `struct Student class[MAX];` | Memory = `MAX * sizeof(Student)` contiguous |
| Accessing *i*-th student's member | `class[i].m1` | The `.` is applied to `class[i]`, not `class` |
| Passing array of structures | `void f(struct Student s[], int n)` | Array decays to pointer automatically |
| Inside function, accessing member | `s[i].m1` | Could also write `(*(&s[i])).m1` — equivalent |
| Computing total | `s[i].total = s[i].m1 + s[i].m2 + s[i].m3;` | Demonstrates struct member as lvalue |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Note on passing:** When an array of structures is passed, you can equivalently use `void f(struct Student *s, int n)`. The notation `s[i]` then becomes pointer arithmetic: `*(s + i)`. KTU accepts both.

