## 3.4 Program 4: Passing a Single Structure to a Function

### Problem Statement
Demonstrate both **pass-by-value** and **pass-by-address** of a structure representing a 2D point `(x, y)`. Show that pass-by-value does *not* modify the original, while pass-by-address *does*.

### Complete Code

```c
#include <stdio.h>

struct Point {
    int x;
    int y;
};

// Pass by VALUE: works on a copy
void moveByValue(struct Point p, int dx, int dy)
{
    p.x += dx;
    p.y += dy;
    printf("Inside moveByValue : (%d, %d)\n", p.x, p.y);
}

// Pass by ADDRESS: modifies the original
void moveByAddress(struct Point *p, int dx, int dy)
{
    p->x += dx;
    p->y += dy;
    printf("Inside moveByAddress: (%d, %d)\n", p->x, p->y);
}

int main(void)
{
    struct Point pt = {10, 20};

    printf("Initial point: (%d, %d)\n", pt.x, pt.y);

    moveByValue(pt, 5, 5);
    printf("After moveByValue : (%d, %d)  <-- unchanged\n",
           pt.x, pt.y);

    moveByAddress(&pt, 5, 5);
    printf("After moveByAddress: (%d, %d)  <-- changed\n",
           pt.x, pt.y);

    return 0;
}
```

### Sample Output

```
Initial point: (10, 20)
Inside moveByValue : (15, 25)
After moveByValue : (10, 20)  <-- unchanged
Inside moveByAddress: (15, 25)
After moveByAddress: (15, 25)  <-- changed
```

### Analytical Matrix — Why the Two Behaviors Differ

| Pass Method | Function Signature | Member Access | Memory Behavior |
|---|---|---|---|
| By Value | `void f(struct Point p, ...)` | `p.x`, `p.y` (dot) | A new copy is made on the stack |
| By Address | `void f(struct Point *p, ...)` | `p->x`, `p->y` (arrow) | Works on the original memory |

The arrow operator is defined as a syntactic shorthand:

$$p \rightarrow m \equiv ( * p ).m$$

This is **mathematically proven** by the C standard and tested directly in KTU questions.

