## 3.5 Program 5: Command Line + Structure Combined (Advanced KTU Pattern)

### Problem Statement
*(High-weightage 14-mark variant)* — Write a C program that accepts the roll number and marks of a student as **command-line arguments** and stores them in a structure. Display the details.

### Complete Code

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>

struct Student {
    int rollNo;
    float marks;
};

int main(int argc, char *argv[])
{
    struct Student s;

    if (argc != 3) {
        printf("Usage: %s <rollNo> <marks>\n", argv[0]);
        return 1;
    }

    s.rollNo = atoi(argv[1]);
    s.marks  = atof(argv[2]);

    printf("--- Student Record ---\n");
    printf("Roll No : %d\n", s.rollNo);
    printf("Marks   : %.2f\n", s.marks);

    return 0;
}
```

### Execution

```bash
./a.out 42 91.5
```

### Output

```
--- Student Record ---
Roll No : 42
Marks   : 91.50
```

### Analytical Derivation of Behavior

Let $A$ = set of command-line tokens supplied by the user, $\vert A \vert = n$.

Then the OS sets:

$$argc = n + 1 \quad \text{(adds the program name)}$$

$$argv[i] = \text{pointer to null-terminated string of token } i, \quad i \in [0, n]$$

For our problem, $n = 2$, so $argc = 3$. The condition `argc != 3` evaluates to *false*, allowing normal flow. The conversions `atoi` and `atof` are applied because all `argv` elements are `char *` — never native numeric types.

