#### Model Solution for (b) — 7 marks

**Concept Explanation:**

| Method | Syntax | Behavior |
|---|---|---|
| Pass by Value | `void f(struct Tag s)` | A *copy* of the structure is passed. Original remains unchanged. |
| Pass by Address | `void f(struct Tag *s)` | The *address* is passed. Original can be modified. |

```c
#include <stdio.h>

struct Box {
    int length;
    int width;
};

// Pass by value: works on a copy
void doubleSizeByValue(struct Box b)
{
    b.length *= 2;
    b.width  *= 2;
    printf("Inside ByValue: %d x %d\n", b.length, b.width);
}

// Pass by address: modifies the original
void doubleSizeByAddress(struct Box *b)
{
    b->length *= 2;
    b->width  *= 2;
    printf("Inside ByAddr : %d x %d\n", b->length, b->width);
}

int main(void)
{
    struct Box myBox = {10, 5};

    printf("Original: %d x %d\n", myBox.length, myBox.width);

    doubleSizeByValue(myBox);
    printf("After ByValue : %d x %d  <-- unchanged\n",
           myBox.length, myBox.width);

    doubleSizeByAddress(&myBox);
    printf("After ByAddr  : %d x %d  <-- changed\n",
           myBox.length, myBox.width);

    return 0;
}
```

**Sample Output:**

```
Original: 10 x 5
Inside ByValue: 20 x 10
After ByValue : 10 x 5  <-- unchanged
Inside ByAddr : 20 x 10
After ByAddr  : 20 x 10  <-- changed
```

**Justification (for full 7 marks):** For **large structures** (e.g., a struct with many `double` fields like a 3D mesh), pass-by-value would copy the entire structure onto the function's stack frame, consuming extra time and memory. Pass-by-address transmits only a single pointer (typically 8 bytes on a 64-bit system), making it far more efficient. Therefore, **pass-by-address is preferred for large structures**.

**Mark split (7 marks):**
- Clear concept table — **1 mark**.
- Correct pass-by-value program with dot operator — **2 marks**.
- Correct pass-by-address program with arrow operator — **2 marks**.
- Sound justification of efficiency — **2 marks**.

