## KTU Examiner's Valuation Warning / Pitfall Callout

> [!WARNING]
> **Common mistakes that cost marks in KTU exams:**
>
> 1. **Forgetting the semicolon after `struct` definition:** `struct Student { ... }` — the closing brace MUST be followed by a semicolon. This single missing `;` causes 1–2 mark deductions across the program.
> 2. **Using `&` with array members in `scanf`:** `scanf("%s", &s1.name)` is WRONG. The correct form is `scanf("%s", s1.name)` because `s1.name` decays to a `char *`. Many students lose 1 mark here.
> 3. **Confusing `argv[0]` with the first user argument:** Real KTU questions often ask *"What is `argv[0]`?"* — students wrongly say "the first argument" instead of "the program name".
> 4. **Using `argv[1]` directly in arithmetic without `atoi`:** This is a compilation error. Always write `int x = atoi(argv[1]);`.
> 5. **Wrong choice of operator in functions:** Inside a function receiving `struct Tag *p`, writing `p.x` (dot) instead of `p->x` (arrow) is a compilation error. KTU examiners deduct the full 7 marks if the program fails to compile.
> 6. **Integer division in average computation:** `sum / 3` instead of `sum / 3.0f` produces wrong output (e.g., 5 instead of 5.00).
> 7. **Forgetting `#include <stdlib.h>`** when using `atoi`/`atof` — the compiler may issue an implicit declaration warning, costing you the execution marks.

